<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Schedule for Partnership for Peace Plan Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401111794 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 0600 
GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2401111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Partnership for Peace plan is not an offer of 
alliance. What it offers to European states is cooperation in 
the military and political spheres. This is what Foreign 
Minister Josef Zieleniec said on television. Asked about the 
schedule for the Czech Republic joining NATO, the minister 
replied: 
  [Begin Zieleniec recording] It much depends on the general 
development of the security situation in the world. I think that 
a tacit part of the agreement is that the plan will acquire 
greater dynamism in the event that the situation on the 
continent and also in East Europe deteriorates. On the other 
hand, if developments proceed along the lines of peace and calm 
and if they are heading toward democracy in all East and Central 
European states, there could be some delay. But, in that case, 
there would be no risk to our security. [end recording]. 
  Josef Zieleniec went on to emphasize that the meaning of 
NATO 
is the provision of joint guarantees for a larger entity sharing 
similar interests, values, and way of life. 
  The immediate opening of NATO toward the deep east and 
embracing states where democracy--and I quote--is not fully 
convincing, would be very risky, Minister Zieleniec said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

