<H3> <TI>   5th Corps Rejects Offer of `Buffer Zones' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101151294 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101151294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Network in Serbo-Croatian at 1400 GMT on 21 January carries in 
its regular 26-minute newscast several reports on the fighting 
in the Republic. 
  Reporting on the situation in Maglaj, Hajrudin Sermic says 
that "over 800 shells have so far today landed on the civilian 
targets and the defensive positions. Civilian casualties have 
been reported. The fighters of the 201st Maglaj Brigade are 
heroically defending the free territory. Heavy losses have been 
inflicted on the united aggressor [the Serbs and the HVO], but 
they do not seem to have had enough as their futile attacks are 
still under way now." 
  Mirudin Aldobasic reports from the operational zone of the 
7th South Operative Group that "since this morning the [Serb] 
enemy on the Doboj front has been shelling Matuzici, Mravici, 
Alibegovci, and (Maslinovac). (Omanjska), (Sivsa), 
(Paradaglije), and Kalosevic on the Tesanj front have also come 
under enemy artillery fire." The report says that "since this 
morning the Mt. Ozren Chetniks from their well-known positions 
have been shelling Lijesnica, (Mekolj), (Omezina), and (?Polje 
Plane)." 
  In his report from Bihac, Mirza Sadikovic says that "it is 
relatively quiet here today, but there has been some sporadic 
small arms fire along the front line with the paraformations of 
the so-called Kladusa autonomy." He cites the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army 5th Corps Command as saying that "it has 
rejected outright the proposal by the other side on establishing 
demarcation lines and some kind of buffer zones. That is 
unacceptable for two reasons, the 5th Corps statement says. 
First, this is an integral part of the territory of the 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, and second, no lines or buffer 
zones can divide our people." 
  The studio announcer says that Sarajevo was "relatively 
quiet 
this morning." 

</TEXT>

