<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Macedonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Passes Law on Denationalization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401210194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2024 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2401210194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 24 Jan (TANJUG) -- At its session today the 
government of the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia passed a 
law on denationalization, which is applicable to all property 
seized by the state without compensation between 2 August 1944 
and 15 February 1968, it was announced in Skopje this evening. 
Implementation of the law will mean the return of property to 
the previous owners, which will take a long time, the Macedonian 
Government says. Among those dispossessed of their property are 
large numbers of the Serbian nationality, who were expelled from 
Macedonia in 1941 by the Bulgarian aggressor, and Josip Broz's 
[Tito's] regime banned their return to their homes. Most of the 
owners and their heirs are now citizens of the Federal Republic 
of Yugoslavia, and a number of them also live abroad. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

