<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Martic Expected To Win Krajina Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401201694 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2401201694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Petko Koprivica from Krajina] </F>
  [Excerpt] The final outcome of the second round of 
presidential elections in the republic of Serbian Krajina is not 
known yet. However, all results so far indicate that 
independent candidate Milan Martic will assume the post of the 
head of this most westerly Serbian state. According to 
unofficial results, Milan Martic won 77,400 votes in 20 out of 
the total of 28 constituencies. The other presidential 
candidate, Milan Babic, received 72,130 votes. The Republican 
Electoral Commission holds the view that Martic's victory is a 
foregone conclusion. Here is what Marijana Puhaca, secretary of 
the aforementioned commission, said about the elections: 
  [Begin Puhaca recording] By 1400 today, the Republican 
Electoral Commission received unofficial results for 19 out of 
the total of 28 constituencies. These 19 constituencies have 
199,274 registered voters. Of these, 140,334 or 58 percent have 
cast their vote. In these 19 constituencies, Milan Babic won 
68,495 votes, and Milan Martic 71,527 votes. 
  By 1400 today, the Republican Electoral Commission received 
official results for only four communes, Drnis, Krnjak, Obrovac, 
and Plaski. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50145 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu016_k_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-016 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wins in Slavonia, Baranja </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401160894 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2401160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Miladin Manojlovic] </F>
  [Text] According to unofficial results of yesterday's 
elections, Milan Martic has convincingly won the second round of 
elections for president of the republic of Serbian Krajina in 
Slavonia, Baranja, and Western Srem. Miladin Manojlovic reports 
from Beli Manastir: 
  [Manojlovic] In Slavonia, Baranja, and Western Srem, Milan 
Martic won 7,070 votes more than Milan Babic. The Vukovar 
electoral unit voters, as in the first round of voting, 
supported Milan Martic the most. He received 15,715 votes and 
Milan Babic received 9,903 votes. Martic won with almost 6,000 
votes more. 
  In other electoral units, the differences are not so great, 
only a few hundred votes more in favor of Martic, except in 
Dalj, where Milan Babic won. Milan Martic won in Beli Manastir, 
Mirkovci, and Tenja. Martic won 651 votes more in Beli 
Manastir, 271 votes more in Mirkovci, and 403 votes more in 
Tenja. Milan Babic won 66 votes more in Dalj. 
  The elections in this region went without any objections 
being raised. The results were verified by observers for both 
presidential candidates. A turnout of over 60 percent, despite 
bad weather, can be considered high and seen as an expression of 
the citizens' will, who confirmed once again the existence and 
resoluteness of the republic of Serbian Krajina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

