<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ammunition Seized From British Ship in Split </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401154894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1400 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2401154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Customs officers in the port of Split have prevented 
the illegal import of military equipment into the territory of 
the Republic of Croatia. The British warship Sir Geraint, 
anchored in the Split port on 21 January, and completed customs 
procedures in possession of valid documents. However, during 
the regular customs inspection, the customs officers discovered 
an irregularity -- namely, one of the eight registered 
containers, declared as dangerous cargo, contained, instead of 
registered gas and petrol, a large amount of ammunition of 
various calibres, military equipment, hand grenades, and 43 
boxes with 14 kg of explosives each. 
  As is the regular procedure according to Croatian 
regulations, which are in line with international laws, a 
commission will be formed to estimate the value of the illegal 
cargo. Criminal charges will be brought against the ship 
commander, while the illegally imported container, already been 
stored in the customs warehouse in Split, will be confiscated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

