<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajina Warns UN of Croatian Aggression </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401185094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1816 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401185094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 24 (TANJUG) -- The foreign minister of 
the republic of Serb Krajina (R.S.K.) Slobodan Jarcevic Monday 
[24 January] warned the U.N. Security Council that Croatia 
wishes to occupy the R.S.K. by military aggression and that it 
is striving to get the approval of the international communty to 
this end. 
  Jarcevic said that the R.S.K., republic proclaimed in 1991 
by 
the Serbs in the territory of the former Yugoslav Republic of 
Croatia where they are in majority, will defend its independence 
with determination. He underlined that the U.N. must help the 
just struggle of the R.S.K. and the right of its people to 
self-determination, guaranteed by the U.N. Charter. 
  Already in 1990, through terror and ethnic cleansing, 
Croatia 
caused the creation of two purely national states in the 
territory of the former Croatia : the Republic of Croatia and 
the R.S.K., Jarcevic said in a letter to the U.N. Security 
Council chairman. Jarcevic was reacting to a letter addressed 
on January 22 to the Security Council by Croatian Foreign 
Minister Mate Granic, demanding that the international community 
help Croatia annex R.S.K. territory. 
  Croatia believes that the joint declaration of the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.) and Croatia on the normalization 
of their relations gives it the green light to occupy the 
R.S.K., he said. Croatian President Tudjman Saturday warned 
that Croatia would recover the R.S.K. territory by other means 
if not through an agreement. The F.R.Y. has signed the 
declaration in order to normalize relations with the Republic of 
Croatia, and not to help Croatia annex the R.S.K. as the 
Croatian minister claimed in his letter, Jarcevic noted. 
  F.R.Y. and Croatian representatives signed on January 19 in 
Geneva a joint declaration on the normalization of their 
relations. Since the former Yugoslav Federation disintegrated, 
the two states have had no economic or political relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50149 </DOCNO>
