<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Comments on Lithuania Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901164294 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1500 
GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Czech Defense Minister Antonin Baudys has ended his 
three-day official visit to Lithuania and returned to Prague. 
Martin Dorazin reports from his news conference: 
  [Dorazin] At a news conference shortly after arriving at the 
old Ruzyne airport, Minister Baudys summed up the contents of 
his visit to Lithuania. During his talks with the Lithuanian 
president, the parliament speaker, and the minister of defense, 
Baudys focused on briefing them on the Partnership for Peace 
project. He also briefed the Lithuanian representatives on our 
attitude toward European security. Let us recall that a desire 
to cooperate with NATO was voiced by representatives of the 
Baltic countries in the so-called letter from three presidents 
to NATO. 
  The Czech minister of defense then got acquainted with the 
situation in the Lithuanian Army, which is undergoing the 
process of building and has problems similar to those of the 
Czech Army. 
  Minister Baudys confirmed that the Czech Republic will grant 
Czech surplus equipment to the Lithuanian Army as a gift. 
  Antonin Baudys expressed mild surprise at the atmosphere 
full 
of trust that accompanied his visit to Lithuania and said that, 
while we have survived socialism, Lithuania survived the USSR. 

</TEXT>

