<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Agreement Yet on Arms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101144694 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 20 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [CTK report: "Baudys Has Offered Lithuania Some of the Czech </F>
Army's Weapons Free of Charge"] 
  [Text] Prague--Although the Czech Army is ready to donate 
submachine guns, tanks, and radio-navigation equipment to the 
Lithuanian Army, a specific agreement on supplies of the Czech 
Army's surplus armaments to Lithuania has not been concluded. 
This statement was made yesterday by Defense Minister Antonin 
Baudys following his return from a visit to Lithuania. 
  According to Baudys, the reason is that the Lithuanian Army 
does not have a clear concept for its structure or for its 
armament program. 
  Baudys said that the Lithuanian Army, in essence, has no 
equipment; however, a much better atmosphere prevails in it than 
in the Czech Army. According to him, this is because Lithuania 
feels more than the Czech Republic that it has to guarantee its 
own security, first and foremost, alone. 

</TEXT>

