<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plan To Trade `Super Dinar' on World Market </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2201105394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1032 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2201105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, January 22 (TANJUG)--The Yugoslav national 
currency might soon join convertible currencies on the world 
money market because the new dinar will be fully convertible, 
Professor Dr. Dragoslav Avramovic, the author of the programme 
for the country's monetary reconstruction, has said in an 
interview to TANJUG. The new currency will have 100 percent 
backing in hard currency and gold. At the very onset of the 
programme, it will be backed by half a billion dollars, he said. 
  The implementation of the programme for the monetary 
reconstruction will begin on Monday, January 24, and its primary 
objective will be to curb the world record hyperinflation, which 
amounted to one million percent in December. The old dinar will 
remain in circulation in parallel with the convertible dinar, 
but the government has decided to stop the issue of money which 
has no backing. 
  The author of the idea of a "super dinar" said that the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (Serbia and Montenegro), in spite 
of being under severe international sanctions for 20 months, has 
managed to secure a hard currency backing for the reconstruction 
of its monetary and fiscal system. The state should stimulate 
the return of capital which entrepreneurs, private banks and 
firms took out of the country in the past few years, since this 
could be the most substantial "outside" support to the new 
programme at the present time because of the financial blockade, 
Avramovic said. 
  The exact amount of this capital is not clear--an estimated 
five billion dollars or more--but it would be a significant 
financial backing for the programme in its entirety for a 
long-term period, especially to the convertibility of the dinar. 
  Experts of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) last week 
turned down a Yugoslav Government request to join in the 
formulation of the stabilization programme. 
  The United Nations (U.N.) Sanctions Committee has not 
answered Yugoslavia's request of December last year to thaw at 
least part of its hard currency reserves in foreign banks, which 
were frozen 20 months ago when the implementation of the U.N. 
sanctions began. Under the government programme, these funds 
would serve as a backing for the new sound national currency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

