<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Britain, France Considering Pulling Out Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101182394 Paris AFP in English 1811 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101182394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] London, Jan 21 (AFP) -- Britain and France said 
Friday [21 January] that the option of pulling all United 
Nations troops out of Bosnia-Herzegovina, possibly as early as 
this spring, was being given serious consideration. [passage 
omitted] 
  In other developments Friday, Bosnian Prime Minister Haris 
Silajdzic hailed an agreement signed Tuesday between Belgrade 
and Zagreb to normalize their relations, saying it could be a 
turning point in the peace process. 
  Speaking after returning from Geneva, he said that the 
agreement "could serve as a solid base for re-establishing 
peace." 
  "We are ready to take part in a peace process on a new basis 
of mutual recognition of former Yugoslav republics which have 
already been internationally recognized," he said. 
  In Bosnia itself the situation was calm on most fronts for a 
second successive day, according to officials. UN Protection 
Force spokesman Bill Aikman said Thursday had been the calmest 
day for months. 
  However Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic said that 
Bosnian Moslems were preparing to attack Serb positions across 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  He made the comments in a letter to Greek officials who had 
invited him to Athens Friday. He cancelled the trip at the last 
minute because of what he called the "new difficulties." 
  "A vast Moslem attack on all our positions is being 
prepared... I must work at the same time for peace and work to 
defend my country," he said, excusing himself from the Athens 
trip. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50166 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu016_r_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-016 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iliescu Comments After Talks With PDSR </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401195894 Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA in Romanian 21 Jan 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU2401195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with President Ion Iliescu by Dorina Baesu in </F>
Bucharest on 20 January: "Brief Interview With Mr. Ion Iliescu 
After the Talks Between the Social Democracy Party of Romania 
and the President: `I Agree With Salagean'"] 
  [Text] [Baesu] Today, during your talks with the Social 
Democracy Party of Romania [PDSR], the PDSR leaders asked you to 
further remain actively involved in the negotiations it will 
conduct with the opposition. Are you going to do that? 
  [Iliescu] This is what I am actually doing. I believe that 
today's discussions with the PDSR are the start of the second 
stage of the meetings with all parties. I will stay involved. 
  [Baesu] Therefore, the negotiations with the opposition -- 
which, in the opinion of Mr. Nastase [PDSR executive president], 
are bound to last a long time -- will begin. Until then, a 
coalition government between the PDSR and the Romanian National 
Unity Party [PUNR] will be formed. Will this coalition not 
damage the country's image? 
  [Iliescu] It might do some damage, but this is the formula 
that resulted from the discussion. 
  [Baesu] But why was it absolutely necessary to form a 
government with the PUNR? 
  [Iliescu] This is not necessary, but inevitable. 
  [Baesu] Why? 
  [Iliescu] Because it offers stability, for the time being. 
  [Baesu] PUNR senator Viorel Salagean claims that such a 
government will not only damage the country's image, but it will 
not last too long, either. 
  [Iliescu] I agree with Salagean, but the party should also 
agree with him. 
  [Baesu] What do you have to say about the fact that several 
politicians, including Adrian Nastase, were accused by Corneliu 
Vadim Tudor [president of the Greater Romania Party-PRM] of 
being CIA spies? 
  [Iliescu] This is stupid and despicable. He could be sued 
for that. It is proof of his irresponsibility. 
  [Baesu] Nevertheless, the PRM is still the PDSR's ally. Is 
such an alliance not being perceived negatively? 
  [Iliescu] I agree with you. It is perceived rather badly. 
  [Baesu] Then, what should be done to ensure that the PDSR is 
no longer obliged to have such an ally as the PRM? 
  [Iliescu] We must create another political climate, of 
understanding among the democratic forces. However, I would 
like to emphasize that I do not identify the parties with their 
figures. A man is not a party. As a matter of fact -- I do not 
want to name any names right now -- there are certain elements 
in the Democratic Convention (people -- our editorial note), 
that are by no means any more credible or desirable than some 
individuals from the current majority. 
  [Baesu] Still, none of the Convention's leaders has ever 
made a statement like Corneliu Vadim Tudor's. 
  [Iliescu] Well, let me assure you that they have made quite 
a few statements, and how! 
  [Baesu] Can you give some concrete examples... 
  [Iliescu] Is there a need for examples? By the way, what 
newspaper do you work for? 
  [Baesu] ROMANIA LIBERA. 
  [Iliescu] You see? Just the insolence of the writings of 
Petre Mihai Bacanu and Octavian Paler would suffice as examples 
of that. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

