<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac in Warsaw for Talks With Walesa </TI></H3>
<H4>   Leaders Want Cooperation </H4>
<F P=102> LD2501165794 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1500 
GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2501165794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Slovak President Michal Kovac today started his 
official visit to Poland. Miroslav Karas, our Warsaw 
correspondent, reports: 
  [Karas] After his arrival by air shortly before noon, Michal 
Kovac first met his Polish counterpart for a half-hour talk. 
Lech Walesa stressed to journalists that this was the first 
visit of the president of independent Slovakia to Poland. We 
are neighbors, and we want to be good neighbors. We have a lot 
of internal political and economic problems, but their solution 
will bring us common results. I wish that nothing concerning us 
be undertaken in Europe without us. Regional cooperation is the 
future for the Europe of the 21st century, which will lead to 
the disappearance of borders, the Polish president said. 
  According to Michal Kovac, the Slovak Republic considers 
friendship with Poland one of the most important cornerstones in 
the building of the international position of Slovakia. For the 
first time in history, a situation has been created in which not 
only Slovakia and Poland, but more countries of the Central 
European region, have common and identical interests, the Slovak 
president said and added that, even if we are trying to overcome 
the division of Europe, we realize that it will be a long-term 
and complicated process, and one has to realize the fact that 
the countries of the Visegrad Group have their specific 
interests in this process. 
  In this connection, Kovac stressed that the Slovak Republic 
realizes the great significance of the mutual cooperation of the 
Visegrad Group countries in the sphere of security. Accepting 
the Partnership for Peace plan, which we will be concluding with 
NATO individually, should be an incentive for better cooperation 
and exchange of experiences. I am convinced that cooperation of 
the Visegrad Four is the most important thing we can contribute 
toward becoming bona fide members of NATO, Slovak President 
Michal Kovac said. 
  In the afternoon, he met Polish Prime Minister Waldemar 
Pawlak, the minister of foreign economic relations, and Cardinal 
Glemp. 

</TEXT>

