<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia To Double Natural Gas Deliveries </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2001115794 Bratislava NARODNA OBRODA in Slovak 12 Jan 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> AU2001115794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava NARODNA OBRODA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Rem Ivanovich Vyachirev, president of the </F>
Russian GAZPROM gas company, by Vladimir Duduc, in Bratislava on 
10 January: "Doubling of Deliveries; Preliminary Agreement on 
Gas Imports From Russia"] 
  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] [Duduc] We know that, while in 
Bratislava, you discussed natural gas deliveries to Slovakia. 
What are your conditions? 
  [Vyachirev] Our talks were concluded with the signing of a 
protocol that affirms the two sides' interest in advantageous 
bilateral cooperation. [passage omitted] The Russian Federation 
is interested in increasing natural gas deliveries to the 
countries of Western Europe via the Slovak Republic's transit 
gas pipeline system. Your side, on the other hand, is asking for 
more gas from Russia. We have agreed that experts of both 
countries meet in Bratislava or Moscow by the end of the first 
quarter of this year to specify the amount by which [Slovak] 
natural gas imports will be increased. According to preliminary 
agreements, the increase should be in the range of 4-5 billion 
cubic meters, which is approximately twice the amount the Slovak 
Republic has been importing thus far. 
  [Duduc] Have you also come to an agreement on prices? 
  [Vyachirev] No, we did not discuss prices. Even if we did, I 
would not reply to your question because it is a commercial 
secret. I would not tell anyone. 
  [Duduc] Did you also discuss the modernization of existing 
gas pipelines or the construction of new ones? 
  [Vyachirev] We have agreed on a fraternal division of labor. 
Everyone will do his job on his own territory--Russia on Russian 
territory and Slovakia on Slovak territory. 

</TEXT>

