<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec: No Timetable for NATO Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401115194 Prague CTK in English 1649 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 23 (CTK) -- Czech Foreign Minister 
Josef Zieleniec said today that no timetable had been set for 
the Partnership for Peace plan because admission of new members 
into NATO could be accelerated if security situation worsened. 
Speaking in a Czech Television's discussion program, Arena, 
Zieleniec said that the Czech Republic's entrance into NATO 
would depend on the development of the security situation in 
Europe. 
  "If the developments are calm, peaceful, and heading for 
democracy in all Eastern and Central European states, ... the 
Czech Republic's admission into NATO may be protracted, but this 
will pose no risk to our security," Zieleniec said. He added 
that he did not think the country would now be facing any urgent 
threat. 
  Zieleniec said it was in the Czech Republic's interest that 
the neighbor countries belong to the same political-military 
bloc. "No one wants its own border to be the border of 
confrontation," he said. He dismissed as false all press 
considerations about the Czech Republic's wish to join NATO 
before its neighbors. But Zieleniec said that the North 
Atlantic Alliance, which jointly guarantees a bigger entity, had 
to be effective. The immediate opening of NATO deep eastwards 
and embracing states where democracy "is not yet fully 
convincing" would be risky. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

