<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows ODS Leading With 32 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2001190594 Prague CTK in English 1618 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2001190594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 18 (CTK) -- If parliamentary elections 
were held today, the Civic Democratic Party (ODS) would win with 
32 percent of the vote, according to an opinion poll carried out 
among 1,561 respondents over age 18 by the Center for Empirical 
Research (STEM) at the beginning of January. In second place, 
according to the research, would be the Civic Democratic 
Alliance (ODA) with 14 percent of the vote. The Czech Social 
Democratic Party (CSSD) would gain 13 percent, the Communist 
Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSCM) 9 percent and the Christian 
Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL) 6 percent. 
  Those parties winning less than 5 percent of the vote -- the 
cutoff for parliamentary representation -- would be the radical 
right-wing Assembly for the Republic-Czechoslovak Republican 
Party (SPR-RSC) with 4 percent, the Free Democrats (SD -- 
formerly the Civic Movement) with 2.5 percent, the 
Moravian-Silesian Centrist Party (MSS -- formerly the Movement 
for Self-Governing Democracy for Moravia and Silesia) with 2 
percent, and the Greens and the Christian Democratic Party (KDS) 
with 1.5 percent each. 
  The four parties making up the current governing coalition 
are the ODS, the ODA, the KDU-CSL, and the KDS. 
  The research indicated that 63 percent of eligible voters 
would take part in the elections, while 14 percent would 
definitely not vote and 23 percent are still undecided. The 
ODS, the KDU-CSL, and the KSCM show the greatest stability of 
voter preference. The CSSD has experienced a drop in 
popularity, while the ODA has gained favor among voters. 
Supporters of the ODS are the most strongly convinced of their 
preference, and 83 percent would vote in elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

