<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dlouhy: Temelin Nuclear Plant To Be Completed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401190894 Prague CTK in English 1813 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 24 (CTK) -- Differing views on the use 
of nuclear energy will not prevent cooperation and good 
relations between Austria and the Czech Republic, Trade and 
Industry Minister Vladimir Dlouhy said today. He said that 
during his talks with Environment Minister Maria Rauch-Kallat in 
Vienna last Thursday [20 January], Austria's stand was partially 
changed and Austria now respected the principle of 
non-interference in the internal affairs of the Czech Republic, 
including decisions by the Czech Government. It is therefore 
possible to complete the construction of two blocks of the south 
Bohemian nuclear power plant at Temelin, some 100 kilometers 
from the Austrian border, Dlouhy said. 
  The issue of the construction of a temporary storage 
facility 
for nuclear waste in Dukovany, south Moravia, was also 
negotiated. The Czech side feels that Austrian opinions should 
be presented only on the basis of international agreements while 
the Czech Republic proposes meetings to be held between experts 
from both countries, Dlouhy said. 

</TEXT>

