<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nine Deputies Split From Left Bloc Over Name </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101074094 Prague CTK in English 1344 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 20 (CTK) -- Eight parliamentarians from 
the Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSCM) and one 
independent deputy, until now members of the Left Bloc (LB) 
deputies' group, founded a new group after they failed on 
Wednesday [19 January] to assert a change in the LB group's 
name, Vaclav Exner told CTK today. Exner, the KSCM deputy 
chairman, heads the new group. 
  The nine deputies left Wednesday's session of the LB group 
before a vote was taken on the proposal to change the group's 
name. Eventually, the remaining deputies decided to retain the 
name Left Bloc, but it will be followed with the abbreviations 
of the names of the three parties comprising it, listed in 
brackets. The three parties are the Left Bloc Party (SLB), the 
KSCM and the Democratic Left Party (SDL). 
  Originally the Left Bloc group consisted of the KSCM, the 
Democratic Left, and several smaller entities. On the basis of 
the June 1992 election results, the LB got 35 out of the total 
of 200 parliamentary seats and formed the second strongest group 
in the parliament. 
  The original number of nine parliamentary groups has 
increased to 11 due to various changes affecting non-government 
party groups. 

</TEXT>

