<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Condemns Extreme Right-Wing Party </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2001162694 Budapest MTI in English 1042 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2001162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 20 January (MTI) -- The activity of the 
World National Popular Rule Party, an extreme-right group under 
the banner of World War II Hungarian fascist leaders, is 
unacceptable and beyond contempt for the government, said 
spokeswoman Judit Juhasz in a statement carried by the daily 
NEPSZABADSAG on Thursday. Juhasz spoke to the daily after the 
party, registered in October 1993, held a meeting on Tuesday of 
about 50 people. At the meeting, the party claimed to succeed 
the Hungarian fascist arrow-cross party of the 1930's and 
1940's, and denied the Holocaust ever took place. 
  The new group reportedly wants to rehabilitate arrow-cross 
leader Ferenc Szalasi, who unleashed a reign of terror when his 
party came to power in 1944. He was executed in 1946 for crimes 
against humanity. 
  Juhasz regretted that Registration Court party synopses 
often 
differ from actual intentions. "The real motives and aims of 
these parties become clear only at their meetings and in their 
public statements." The Tuesday meeting makes this group 
unacceptable for the government and it violates constitutional 
order, Juhasz said. Asked by NEPSZABADSAG, she said the 
government feels constitutionally obliged to act against all 
forms of discrimination. At the commemoration of the liberation 
of the Budapest ghetto on Tuesday, the cabinet was represented 
by three ministers, signalling the government's clear position, 
Juhasz said. 

</TEXT>

