<H3> <TI>   Sejm Deputy Appeals for Larger Defense Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501182094 Warsaw PAP in English 1552 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wroclaw, Jan. 25 -- Head of the Sejm Committee for 
National Defence Jerzy Szmajdzinski said that the condition of 
Polish Army's equipment is so poor that the Army will soon "run 
into cannibalism" by eating up its own reserves. Addressing a 
press conference in Wroclaw on Tuesday, Szmajdzinski warned that 
the daily costs of maintaining the complex military training, 
health care, and housing systems represent 75 percent of the 
total Army budget because these structures are too large for the 
reduced Polish Army. Szmajdzinski called for respective quick 
decisions because even a 6-7 percent increase in spending on 
national defence will not solve the problem. He also appealed 
for quicker structural changes in the national defence sector 
and exemption of 5 thousand soldiers from the military service 
duty. 

</TEXT>

