<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik: European Security Depends on Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401114694 Prague CTK in English 1900 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401114694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Jan 23 (CTK) -- Slovak Foreign Minister 
Jozef Moravcik said today that the question of European security 
could not be solved without Russia's participation. Speaking in 
a Slovak Television discussion program "Kroky" (Steps), Moravcik 
said that there was no reason for Russia to feel threatened by a 
possible eastwards expansion of NATO. He said the apprehension 
could be removed by the signature of a package of agreements 
between Russia and Nato. 
  Russian Ambassador to Slovakia Sergey Yastrzhembskiy said 
that the Partnership for Peace plan had dispelled Russia's fears 
of a new power division of Europe. He said that a large portion 
of the Russian society, brought up in the totalitarian faith 
that the NATO countries were its major enemies, disagreed with 
the pact's expansion. To overlook this would strengthen the 
positions of Russian ultra-nationalist forces, Yastrzhembskiy 
stressed. If this situation is to be coped with, no "overhasty" 
expansion of the pact must be allowed, Russia must be given an 
active role in the implementation of the partnership, a treaty 
between the alliance and Moscow could be signed. 
  U.S. Ambassador to Slovakia Theodore Russell said that 
Moscow's fears could be best dispelled if Russia joined the 
Partnership for Peace. 
  Slovak Defense Minister Imrich Andrejcak said Slovakia was 
intensively drafting a law providing for civil control of the 
Armed Forces, one of the conditions of the partnership. Under 
the law, two thirds of the Defense Ministry's staff are to be 
civilians. Russell praised the Slovak approach to the plan. 
  Moravcik confirmed once again that Slovakia's goal was 
fully-fledged membership of NATO, adding that the Partnership 
for Peace was the "entrance gate" to it. 

</TEXT>

