<H3> <TI>   `Contradictory Statements' in Minority Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401104494 Prague CTK in English 2148 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Jan 22 (CTK) -- Milan Zemko from the 
Slovak Presidential Office today said that the contradictory 
statements and moves by the parliament and government "are 
narrowing the scope for negotiations with Hungarian partners," 
Slovak Radio reported. Speaking at a discussion-meeting 
organized by the Forum Foundation, Zemko was reacting to the 
current tense situation among the Hungarian ethnic minority 
which is 560,000-strong and which constitutes 11 percent of 
Slovakia's population. The Hungarians criticize the Slovak 
authorities of not observing minority rights, and they have 
called for autonomy in southern Slovakia, where most of them 
live. Jan Carnogursky, chairman of the opposition Christian 
Democratic Movement (KDH), said that as early as 1987 
cooperation between the Hungarian and Slovak dissidents had been 
subdued due to the Hungarians' unwillingness to recognize the 
inviolability of the existing Slovak-Hungarian border. 

</TEXT>

