<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Comment on New Military Budget </TI></H3>
<H4>   General Staff Chief Cited </H4>
<F P=102> AU2401115794 Sofia DEMOKRATSIYA in Bulgarian 19 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401115794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia DEMOKRATSIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nedko Petrov: "The Chief of the General Staff </F>
Would Not Resign"] 
  [Text] On 18 January Army General Lyuben Petrov, chief of 
the General Staff, invited correspondents who cover Army issues 
to the Central Army Club in Sofia. Despite the fact that it was 
previously announced that the meeting would not be a news 
conference, the General Staff chief answered several questions 
regarding problems in the Bulgarian Army. General Petrov 
considers the new military budget extremely insufficient for the 
Army, especially since war is raging along our western border. 
However, the Army chief said that contrary to reports that 
appeared immediately after the draft military budget was 
published, even if the budget is adopted, he would not resign. 
"I will not desert the Army, but I also will not be held 
responsible for the Bulgarian Army's combat readiness, " General 
Petrov said. 
  The General Staff chief admitted participating in working 
out 
the presidential decree on the functions and prerogatives of the 
president's Military Office but refused to comment on the issue 
until the National Security Commission takes a stand. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

