<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy Cited on UNPROFOR Smuggling Inquiry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501211994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1755 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501211994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 25 (TANJUG) -- Branko Brankovic, 
ambassador at the Yugoslav Foreign Ministry, Tuesday [25 
January] said that the investigation into malversations 
committed by UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] members had 
political, in addition to moral, aspects, as some U.N. force 
members had organized arms smuggling into Bosnia-Herzegovina in 
spite of the U.N. embargo on arms deliveries to the former 
Yugoslavia. This arms smuggling has helped Moslems arm 
themselves, Brankovic told Radio Yugoslavia. Brankovic also 
recalled that the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia had warned on 
time that someone within the UNPROFOR was involved in secreat 
arms deliveries to the Moslem forces in the civil war-torn 
former Yugoslav Republic. 
  After several months of investigtion, a special U.N. 
commission proved that some UNPROFOR members were involved in 
illegal traffic in fuel, passes for departure from the Moslem 
part of Sarajevo and stolen goods, as well as in prostitution. 
Brankovic said it was good to have the U.N secretary general 
order the investigation, as it has proved that only a small part 
of the UNPROFOR and not the entire force was involved in illegal 
activities. 
  Truths which had been hidden from the public for a long time 
are now being unveiled, as proved by the interview given by the 
former UNPROFOR Commander in Bosnia General Francis Briquemont 
to the WASHINGTON POST, unequivocally stating that only Bosnian 
Serbs abide by their commitments, Brankovic said. Without any 
doubt in many cases, UNPROFOR had been presenting to relevant 
U.N. bodies true reports on what was happening in the field in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. However, these reports were placed ad acta 
or passed over in silence, whether in UPROFOR headquarters in 
Zagreb or New York, Brankovic said. 
  It is to be expected that UNPROFOR reports will from now on 
get the green light on time, i.e. that the international public 
opinion will be informed of them, Ambassador Brankovic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50247 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu017_y_94002" </HT>


