<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Previews Visit to Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701102694 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
0700 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2701102694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Hungarian foreign minister will travel to 
Yugoslavia today. Prior to his talks, he gave an interview to 
MAGYAR SZO, the paper of Vojvodina Hungarians. Arpad Madarasz 
reports from Novi Sad. 
  [Madarasz] It is a fundamental interest of the two 
neighboring peoples to live in peace and good-neighborliness 
with each other, the Hungarian foreign minister told the Novi 
Sad paper MAGYAR SZO. Geza Jeszenszky stressed that Hungary 
wishes to have friendly relations with every southern Slav 
people, and from the beginning of the crisis it has been 
striving to establish well balanced ties with each successor 
state of the disintegrating Yugoslavia. 
  First of all, I would like to see and experience personally 
how people live in Yugoslavia today and how it feels to be a 
Hungarian in Vojvodina, said Jeszenszky. He added that he does 
not expect spectacular results from the visit and talks. 
However, he expects us to confirm that it is our mutual 
determination to improve interstate ties gradually, step by 
step, taking the possibilities into consideration, to restore 
confidence. 
  The Hungarian Government supports the autonomy concept of 
the 
Democratic Community of Hungarians in Vojvodina [VMDK], but it 
does not regard it as its task to discuss this with the Yugoslav 
Government, Geza Jeszenszky pointed out. However, he said he is 
pleased to learn that President Milosevic has invited [VMDK 
leader] Andras Agoston to attend the talks. 

</TEXT>

