<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hopes for Improved Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701154794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1443 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2701154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 27 January (TANJUG) -- The foreign 
ministers of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and Hungary, 
Vladislav Jovanovic and Geza Jeszensky, today spoke in favor of 
resuming contacts and goodneighborly cooperation. 
  "I have always valued goodneighborly relations. I hope that 
despite the current situation it will be possible to improve 
Yugoslav-Hungarian relations," Geza Jeszensky said at Belgrade 
airport upon his arrival from Budapest at the start of a two-day 
official visit to the FRY. 
  The Hungarian foreign minister said that conditions for 
cooperation had changed over the last few years but went on to 
express hope that there was scope for improving relations, 
especially in the humanitarian sphere, despite changed 
circumstances. In this context he described Vojvodina 
Hungarians as a "bridge for cooperation" and said that there was 
an opportunity currently for them to remain so. 
  Federal Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic said that he 
expected good results in Yugoslav-Hungarian talks but noted that 
it remained to be seen what could be objectively achieved. He 
added that now was the right moment to renew talks and contacts. 

</TEXT>

