<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPS Nominates Candidate for Assembly Chairman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2601152994 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2601152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Serbian assembly has been holding a 
consultative session for three days and yet the chairman of the 
assembly has not been elected, not even in the morning part of 
the session. The assembly is currently in recess until 1600 
[1500 GMT] so that the heads of the deputy caucuses can reach an 
agreement. Srdjan Savic reports: 
  [Savic] At the beginning of the session, chairman Vojislav 
Dimitrijevic told deputies that he had received a new nomination 
only from the Socialist Party of Serbia for the post of the 
chairman of the assembly. The party's new candidate is Dragan 
Tomic, head of the party's deputy caucus. 
  Vuk Draskovic, president of the Serbian Renewal Movement, 
explained why DEPOS [Democratic Movement of Serbia] had not 
proposed its new candidate today. He said that the parliament's 
left and right parties' attempts to outvote one another were in 
vain, and that it was necessary to reach a political agreement 
on the division of responsibility for the legislative, 
executive, and judiciary authorities. The Socialists bear the 
greatest responsible for all compromises and agreements, because 
they are the first party on the political ladder, Draskovic 
said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50262 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu018_y_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-018 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
