<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Urges Media To Demonstrate `Integrity' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701123694 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1105 
GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2701123694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak visited the 
Polish Press Agency [PAP] this morning. During a brief meeting 
of the agency management he spoke about the need for 
journalistic integrity. 
  [Begin Pawlak recording] I hope that PAP will deal with 
facts 
and information related to facts and not with spreading feelers 
put out by other media. This, I think, is a general issue that 
concerns mass media in general, to concentrate on facts -- and 
on important facts -- and not make a huge story out of minor 
matters. It often happens that once a story is verified it is 
hard to tell where it originated, but by that time it is all 
over the place. 
  So, I think that such an agency as PAP should serve as an 
example of reliability and publish information that is important 
to the public, the state, and the economy. [end recording] 
  Asked what feelers he had in mind, Prime Minister Pawlak 
recalled the issue of the Concordat. 
  [Begin Pawlak recording] There was a situation when a well 
known local radio set in motion an avalanche of suppositions, 
speculations, and considerations around alleged expert reports. 
Later, when there was a joint statement by the government and 
episcopate press offices, it seemed like the reports could 
hardly get through. 
  I understand that sensations should find their way to the 
consumers, but journalistic integrity requires equal treatment 
of information concerning facts and correction of information if 
it is untrue. But it would be best not to deal with untrue 
information at all. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

