<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Diminishing Support for Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2601145694 Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA in Polish 26 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> WS2601145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by B.I.W.: "CBOS: A Cabinet for More Than a Year"] </F>
  [Text] Since December, support for the government has been 
on the wane; nevertheless, the government still has more 
supporters (45 percent) than opponents (18 percent). Almost 50 
percent of respondents to a public opinion poll believe that the 
present government will stay in power for more than a year. 
  Over the last two years, the number of people who support 
the 
idea of increasing the president's influence on the work of the 
government has decreased. Forty percent of respondents believe 
that the policy of the government offers a chance for overcoming 
the crisis, even though since November the number of optimists 
has decreased quite noticeably (by almost 15 percent). For the 
first time since the Pawlak government was formed, 37 percent of 
Poles are of the opinion that this government is neither better 
nor worse than the previous one; 34 percent believe it is better. 
  This research study was conducted by the Public Opinion 
Research Center [CBOS] between 14 and 17 January with a 
representative sample of adult Poles. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

