<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukrainian Foreign Minister Visits </TI></H3>
<H4>   Signs Protocols </H4>
<F P=102> LD2601175094 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2601175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Croatian Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister 
Mate Granic and Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko 
signed a protocol in Zagreb today on cooperation between the 
Croatian and Ukrainian ministries of foreign affairs and a 
protocol on establishing consular relations. 
  We are new independent states and therefore we have mutual 
interests in many spheres. We would primarily wish to develop 
political cooperation, but also economic cooperation, as we have 
good conditions for this, Ukrainian Minister Anatoliy Zlenko 
stated following the signing of the documents. 
  We had talks on the political situation in the region, the 
situation in Croatia and Ukraine, the promotion of economic 
relations which lag behind the political will, and on political 
relations, because there are no open questions between Ukraine 
and Croatia, Mate Granic stated. He announced that treaties on 
friendship and cooperation between the two states, treaties on 
economic, cultural, medical, and transport cooperation, and 
several other important documents are being prepared. 
  The Croatian minister informed journalists that his talks 
with the Ukrainian minister also referred to all important 
issues in Croatian and Ukrainian foreign policy. Minister 
Granic also informed the Ukrainian minister about the Geneva 
negotiations, his visit to Italy in February, and Croatia's 
desire to be admitted to the Council of Europe and to join the 
Partnership for Peace program. 

</TEXT>

