<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Warring Sides Discuss Humanitarian, Military Issues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Srpska Official Comments </H4>
<F P=102> LD2601235794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2341 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2601235794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Sarajevo, Jan 26 (TANJUG) -- Bosnia-Herzegovina's 
warring Moslems, Serbs and Croats signed late on Wednesday a 
declaration undertaking to protect the power facilities in this 
war-torn former Yugoslav Republic. 
  Bosnian Serb Vice-President Nikola Koljevic told reporters 
after the first round of talks at Sarajevo Airport that the 
document regulated all power disruptions in territories 
controlled by all three sides. 
  The talks at Sarajevo Airport are part of an effort to 
rebuild confidence among Bosnia's warring nations. 
  No agreement has been reached on another major issue -- the 
release of five Serb doctors and three nurses arrested by the 
Moslems in Sarajevo last week in an alleged attempt to flee a 
Moslem-controlled quarter of the city. 
  "This issue should demonstrate the good will of the (Moslem) 
side, and we regret to say that we shall be unable to accept any 
agreement until this major issue has been resolved," said 
Koljevic. 
  General Milan Gvero, assistant commander of the Bosnian Serb 
Army, said the Moslem military authorities had been asked to 
publicly withdraw their declaration of war on the Serbs in these 
lands and to clearly call off all military operations, as 
insistence on confidence-building is senseless if combat 
operations continue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

