<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims Intensify Attacks on Bosnian Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601163294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1604 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2601163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Bratunac, Jan 26 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Moslem troops 
continued and intensified on Wednesday attacks in several 
directions on the positions and settlements of Bosnian Serbs, 
Bosnian Serb Republic army sources reported. 
  According to the same sources, Moslem forces fired from 
infantry arms, grenade launchars, snipers and mortars on the 
Serbian districts of Sarajevo -- Grbavica, Dobrinja one and 
Dobrinja four, Lukavica, Nedjarice, Ilidza, Vogosca and Rajlovac. 
  It is further said that Moslems have renewed attacks on the 
Serbian settlement of Zlatiste near Sarajevo, trying to cut off 
traffic between Sarajevo and Pale, the political and military 
headquarters of Bosnian Serbs in the vicinity of the capital 
city of the former Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Intensified Moslem attacks have also been registered in the 
region of Doboj, Ozren, Maglaj and Zavidovici, while Moslem 
armed provocations persisted near the Teslic, Vlasic, Gradac and 
Trebava battlefields (central Bosnia-Herzegovina). 
  There is no peace either in the region of Gorazde, a Moslem 
enclave in eastern Bosnia-Herzegovina which has been under U.N. 
protection, where Moslem forces persist with their attacks on 
neighbouring Serbian towns of Foca, Cajnice and Ustikolina. 
  Moslem units in the region of Kladanj and Kalesija, in 
eastern Bosnia-Herzegovina, also continued their 
artillery-infantry operations against the Serbian side, Bosnian 
Serb sources said. 

</TEXT>

