<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daskalov Views Relations With Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401082094 Sofia BTA in English 1806 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401082094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, January 23 (BTA) -- "If all of Macedonia's 
neighbours categorically recognize its territorial integrity, 
and if Macedonia does the same about all its neighbours, the 
region will have a firm security guarantee," Bulgarian Foreign 
Minister Stanislav Daskalov said in an interview in the Nedelya 
150 programme on national radio this morning. 
  By its actions, Bulgaria shows clearly it is in favour of 
friendly relations with Macedonia, Mr. Daskalov said, commenting 
on a statement this week by Greek Minister for European Union 
Affairs Theodhoros Pangalos that "the borders of Albania, 
Bulgaria and Serbia with Macedonia are not safe." 
Bulgarian-Macedonian economic contacts are on the fast track, 
Mr. Daskalov also said. Recalling that the presidents of the 
two countries have met twice and that Prime Minister Lyuben 
Berov has visited Skopje, Mr. Daskalov said "political dialogue 
is on a satisfactory level." 
  Asked about Bulgaria's foreign policy priorities in 1993, 
Mr. 
Daskalov said they were prompted by its main objectives, "to 
create conditions guaranteeing Bulgaria's national security and 
economic development." He listed last year's priorities as 
follows: Integration into the European and Euro-Atlantic 
structures, the Balkan scene and relations with the Balkan 
countries, relations with the United States and Russia, the 
Yugoembargo which, in his view, has inflicted serious damage on 
Bulgaria. 

</TEXT>

