<H3> <TI>   Papers Comment on Berov's Address on Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2601132794 Sofia BTA in English 1100 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2601132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From BTA's 26 January "Press Review"] </F>
  [Excerpt] Sofia, January 26 (BTA) -- Yesterday's address 
by Prime Minister Lyuben Berov for a speedier passage of the 
1994 national budget is the main story in today's press. 
According to STANDART NEWS, the prime minister predicted early 
elections. A comment in STANDART NEWS says the prime minister 
played a risky game. "The prime minister forebodes a national 
tragedy if the budget fails to pass by mid-February," says 
KONTINENT. "The ball is now with the Bulgarian Socialist Party 
(BSP, the former Communists) who command a majority in 
parliament and determine the cabinet's fate," says the paper. 
According to OTECHESTVEN VESTNIK, the unrealistic deadline for 
passing the budget is most likely a prime minister move seeking 
to leave government losing as less respect as possible. The 
socialist DUMA says the BSP will make a political decision on 
the budget at a special plenum. A comment in the paper says the 
prime minister's statement sounded like an ultimatum and the 
political forces made it clear this was not a constructive tone. 
"This, however, does not mean the nation is approaching 
elections, as in that case it may end the year without a 
budget," says DUMA. The daily of the Union of Democratic Forces 
(SDS) DEMOKRATSIYA emphasizes Berov called the Socialists 
traitors. "BSP declined to consider the financial programme of 
its own government," says the daily. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

