<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Adopts Decrees on EFTA, EU Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2501074894 Sofia BTA in English 1845 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2501074894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, January 24 (BTA) -- At its regular meeting 
today, the Council of Ministers adopted two decrees related to 
the fulfillment in 1994 of the obligations which Bulgaria 
assumed under its free trade agreement with the member countries 
of the European Free Trade Association (EFTA) and its interim 
trade agreement with the European Union (EU). The adoption of 
these decrees expressly introduces into Bulgaria's domestic 
legislation the obligation to abolish and reduce customs duties 
on certain imports from countries of the two groups. The two 
decrees repeat the clauses in the agreement concerning EFTA and 
EU imports to Bulgaria. The accord with EFTA entered into force 
on July 1, 1993, and the agreement with the EU took effect on 
December 31, 1993. The decrees merely reflect the actual state 
of affairs, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Trade Valentin 
Karabashev told reporters. 
  The decrees adopted today abolish import duties and import 
taxes on crude oil, oils and natural gas, meat for human 
consumption, fish products and canned fish, vegetable oils, 
electricity, ores, chemicals, refractory clay, pharmaceuticals, 
super phosphate fertilizer and rough timber, newspapers, 
dictionaries and books originating from EFTA or EU countries. 
Newsprint, however, will not be exempt from customs duty. 
Import duties on certain foods subject to import quotas under 
the agreements, including citrus fruit, coffee, large cattle, 
poultry and dairy products, are reduced under the decrees. 
  The customs concessions are effective as from January 1, 
1994. The two decrees will be updated annually in compliance 
with the further liberalization moves provided by the agreements 
with EFTA and the EU. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50307 </DOCNO>
