<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel, Poland's Kolodziejczyk View Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2501141494 Prague CTK in English 1319 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2501141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 25 (CTK) -- The process of 
transformation which the Polish Army is currently undergoing is 
very similar to that of the Czech Army, Czech President Vaclav 
Havel said at a meeting with Polish Defense Minister Piotr 
Kolodziejczyk today. The meeting was also attended by Czech 
Defense Minister Antonin Baudys, President's Office Head Lubos 
Dobrovsky told journalists. 
  Havel and Kolodziejczyk agreed that the approach of the 
Czech 
Republic and Poland towards the U.S. Partnership for Peace plan 
was very close and in many points fully identical, he said. 
Havel spoke in favor of continuing consultations and 
cooperation in those fields where they could speed up the 
modernization of armaments systems in the cheapest way. 
  Baudys described Kolodziejczyk's visit as the beginning of a 
broad cooperation between the two countries' armies and defense 
ministries and as the starting point of realizing the necessity 
of a dynamic approach towards the Partnership for Peace project. 
  Kolodziejczyk said NATO standards should be introduced in 
both armies as soon as possible and that they should jointly 
proceed towards a secure Europe. He invited Baudys to visit 
Poland. Kolodziejczyk, who is leaving for home today, was in 
the Czech Republic at Baudys's invitation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50308 </DOCNO>
