<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities Prosecute Arrow Cross `Successor' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401101494 Budapest MTI in English 2030 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 21 Jan (MTI) -- The National Security 
Office today asked MTI to publicize the following statement 
regarding the operation of the World National Popular Rule Party: 
  "The National Security Office of the Republic of Hungary 
lodged an impeachment with the National Police Headquarters 
against Albert Szabo, a dual Hungarian-Australian citizen 
heading the World National Popular Rule Party, and A.B., a 
juvenile activist of the party, on January 21, 1994. They are 
suspected of having committed the crime of incitement against a 
community which is punishable by Par. 269 (1) of the Penal Code." 
  The impeachment followed a Tuesday rally, at which the 
party, 
registered with the Budapest Metropolitan Court in October 1993, 
defined itself as successor to the Hungarian fascist Arrow Cross 
party and its leader, Ferenc Szalasi, who was executed in 1946 
for crimes against humanity. The participants in the rally 
denied that the holocaust had ever taken place. 
  As reported earlier, in Thursday's NEPSZABADSAG, government 
spokeswoman Judit Juhasz said that the Tuesday rally had 
violated constitutional order. She added that the government 
found the activity of the party unacceptable. 

</TEXT>

