<H3> <TI>   Report on Joint Military Exercise Denied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701084794 Budapest MTI in English 1907 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2701084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 26 January (MTI) -- The report of a joint 
Polish-Hungarian-Czech military exercise to be held within the 
framework of Peace Partnership, probably originates from a 
misunderstanding, Lieutenant-Colonel Lajos Erdelyi, spokesman 
for the Ministry of Defence, said on Wednesday [26 January]. 
  MTI's Warsaw correspondent yesterday reported that Polish 
Minister of Defence Piotr Kolodziejczyk, returning from a visit 
to Prague, said on Tuesday evening [25 January] that a military 
exercise of this kind, the largest held within the Peace 
Partnership framework, would be held shortly. 
  Erdelyi said military exercises would definitely be held 
within the Peace Partnership, but no concrete preparations have 
been made so far. NATO member states would also participate, as 
one of the goals is to coordinate with the western military 
forces. 

</TEXT>

