<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Backs Ukrainian Arms Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701152094 Prague CTK in English 1417 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2701152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Jan 27 (CTK) -- Slovakia assesses 
positively the political tendencies in Ukraine aiming at 
creating a nuclear weapon-free state, the Slovak Foreign 
Ministry said in a statement given to CTK today. Ukraine is the 
Slovakia's only neighbor possessing strategic nuclear weapons. 
  Slovakia considers documents on removing nuclear weapons 
from 
Ukrainian territory signed by Ukrainian President Leonid 
Kravchuk, Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President 
Bill Clinton to be an important step on the road towards 
complete nuclear disarmament, the statement said. 
  Under the Moscow agreement, Ukraine is to rid itself of all 
176 nuclear missiles and of almost 1,600 nuclear warheads in 
exchange for aid amounting to one billion U.S. dollars. 
  "We consider this fact proof that even in complicated social 
and economic conditions, it is possible to find compromise 
solutions in the interests of stability and security in Europe. 
Such an approach could serve as example for other states in 
solving other important problems," the statement said. It 
voiced the conviction that all the countries concerned will 
create the conditions necessary for practical realization of the 
documents signed and for fulfilling obligations ensuing from the 
Strategic Arms Treaty (START-1) and the Lisbon protocol. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

