<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Hungarians Complain About `Guarantees' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2601103594 Prague CTK in English 1720 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2601103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Jan 25 (CTK) -- Representatives of the 
coalition Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement (MKDH) and 
Egyutteles turned to the Council of Europe (CE) with a complaint 
about insufficient guarantees for the rights of the ethnic 
minorities in Slovakia, Pal Csaky, a deputy for the MKDH, told 
journalists today. 
  The letter to the CE says that Slovakia is not observing its 
commitments towards the CE regarding ethnic policy, Csaky 
reported. 
  This statement is exemplified by the shortcomings in the 
adopted laws on names and surnames, anomalies in the names of 
Hungarians communities in south Slovakia and the discriminatory 
language law, Csaky said. 
  The so-called alternative educational system, which assumes 
that vocational subjects should be taught in Slovak, is a 
"well-thought out attack on the system of the Hungarian 
schools," Csaky stated. 
  Chairman of the opposition Democratic Left Party (SDL) Peter 
Weiss said that the demands voiced in Komarno (during a meeting 
of ethnic Hungarian representatives on January 8) are 
"exaggerated and tactlessly articulated." They served the 
governing coalition because they deflected public attention from 
the growing economic and social problems, "created the picture 
of an enemy, and pushed the poorly working process of 
privatization to the margin of interest. [no closing quotation 
mark as received] 

</TEXT>

