<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Simic Comments on Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701230494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2041 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2701230494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, 27 Jan (TANJUG) -- Speaking about the 
meeting with his Croatian colleague Mate Granic, Federal Deputy 
Prime Minister Zeljko Simic told TANJUG that the most important 
thing was that today's meeting with representatives of the 
Croatian Government, which lasted nearly six hours, took place 
in a highly tolerant atmosphere. 
  In Simic's assessment, today's meeting is paving the way 
toward the realization of the joint declaration signed by the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and Croatia two weeks ago in 
Geneva. 
  Two exceptionally important proposals were made concrete 
today: To set up a joint commission under the aegis of 
international humanitarian organizations (ICRC [International 
Committee of the Red Cross] and UNHCR). 
  Deputy Prime Minister Simic laid special emphasis on the 
beginning of regular visits by highest-ranking officials from 
Belgrade and Zagreb, which in practice starts on 12 February 
when the FRY deputy prime minister will be received by Croatian 
President Franjo Tudjman. In Simic's opinion, this will, at the 
same time, be an inaugural meeting of the Commission for Missing 
Persons. 
  Serbian-Croatian relations can be successfully resolved only 
through bilateral efforts and this is an example of how to 
tackle the crisis in former Yugoslavia, said the Yugoslav deputy 
prime minister, concluding his statement for TANJUG. 

</TEXT>

