<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar Downplays Concerns of Minority Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701155694 Bratislava REPUBLIKA in Slovak 25 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2701155694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava REPUBLIKA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report: "The Borders Are Unchangeable"] </F>
  [Text] Dunajska Streda--Yesterday's District Assembly of 
the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia [HZDS] in Dunajska Streda 
was attended by HZDS Chairman and Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar. 
  In his opening statement, he pointed out that current HZDS 
district assemblies confirm that the movement is gathering new 
strength and that any opposition pressures are in vain because 
the ruling movement is fulfilling, and will fulfill, its 
electoral program. He noted that, in conformity with the 
Constitution of the Slovak Republic, the movement is trying to 
address ethnic issues so that everyone's freedom and the 
equality of all citizens regardless of nationality be 
guaranteed. No one is a second-class citizen in our country, the 
prime minister stressed. If someone suffers from the internal 
complex of being a second-class citizen, let him undergo 
treatment and not go public with it. 
  Relations among citizens in the south of Slovakia are not 
complicated, but the problems are being exaggerated by Central 
European bodies and also by some circles from Hungary. Our 
borders are unchangeable, and each political party at home as 
well as abroad must realize this, Vladimir Meciar said, among 
other things. 

</TEXT>

