<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Blames Muslims for Continuing War </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801101094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 0023 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2801101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 27 Jan (TANJUG)--Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the republic of Srpska, has sent a letter to UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali, in which he points to 
facts showing that the Muslims in Bosnia are not interested in 
establishing peace. 
  "Muslim Army Commander Rasim Delic reiterated threats 
against 
the Serb side on 25 January, while Muslim Prime Minister Haris 
Silajdzic spoke of the concept of continuing the war in the 
former Bosnia-Herzegovina on 26 January", Karadzic said in his 
letter to Butrus-Ghali. "At the same time, Alija Izetbegovic is 
visiting Muslim countries and is asking for their help, which 
makes us believe that--despite their pretense that they want to 
negotiate--the Muslims really never gave up their aspiration for 
the whole of Bosnia-Herzegovina", Karadzic stresses. According 
to Karadzic, this aspiration is "in conflict with the interests 
of the Serbian and Croatian people in Bosnia." 
  Recalling that the Serbs and the Croats signed an agreement 
on the exchange of official representatives during the last 
round of Geneva negotiations in order to resolve the 
disagreements through political means, Karadzic notes that the 
Muslims were also asked to sign a similar agreement, but did not 
respond. "Muslim demands regarding territorial borders in 
eastern and western Bosnia, which caused the breakup of the 
negotiating process, rendered futile the cochairmen's attempts 
to achieve a result in the peace process that would satisfy all 
three sides in the conflict". 
  In his warning to Butrus-Ghali that Izetbegovic's strategic 
objective is to halt the peace process, Karadzic notes that 
Izetbegovic was essentially trying to buy time for importing 
weapons and strengthening the military option. 
  "Tuzla airport is intended to be used for arms smuggling, 
which would cause new incidents, for which--as usual--the Serbs 
would be blamed", Karadzic warns and points out that the problem 
of humanitarian aid deliveries can be resolved by widening the 
land corridor to Tuzla. "Although humanitarian deliveries would 
double this way, Muslim authorities still insist on opening 
Tuzla airport in an attempt to create a crisis spot", Karadzic 
says, and adds that the "problem" of replacing UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces] troops in Srebrenica has also proven to be 
another Muslim insinuation. "This, however, does not decrease 
the possibility of air strikes against the Serbs, despite the 
fact that such an act could be catastrophic and could cause 
far-reaching complications". 
  Karadzic goes on to say: "If we are attacked, we will 
exercise our legitimate right to self-defense, in which we will 
use all available forces". 
  "Now that Muslim intolerance is the only obstacle to peace, 
I 
cannot understand why the international community should discuss 
such an absurd step for achieving absurd objectives," Karadzic 
says. He adds that the Serbs have fought simply to be able to 
live on the land they had succeeded in preserving through six 
centuries of despotism under the Turkish and Austro-Hungarian 
empires. "We shall fight for another six centuries if need be, 
but we can have peace as early as tomorrow, provided the rights 
of each side are respected", Karadzic says to Ghali. 
  In the conclusion of his letter the president of the Serb 
Republic calls on the UN secretary general to do his utmost to 
encourage U.S. diplomacy to clearly underline to the Muslim 
government in Sarajevo the advantage of peace and the dangers of 
continuing the war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

